    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the GAD-7 questionnaire?</summary>
        <p>The GAD-7 (Generalized Anxiety Disorder 7-item scale) is a brief, validated screening tool developed in 2006. It consists of seven questions that ask how often you have been bothered by specific anxiety symptoms over the past two weeks. Each item is scored from 0 to 3, producing a total score between 0 and 21. It is widely used in primary care and mental health settings to screen for generalized anxiety disorder and monitor treatment progress. You can <a href="/test/anxiety-test/">take our free anxiety screening</a> to see your score.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What do GAD-7 scores mean?</summary>
        <p>GAD-7 scores fall into four severity ranges: 0-4 indicates minimal anxiety, 5-9 indicates mild anxiety, 10-14 indicates moderate anxiety, and 15-21 indicates severe anxiety. A score of 10 or above is commonly used as the clinical threshold at which further professional evaluation is recommended. The score reflects symptom severity over the past two weeks and is useful for tracking changes over time, but it is not a diagnosis by itself.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can you diagnose anxiety with the GAD-7 alone?</summary>
        <p>No. The GAD-7 is a screening tool, not a diagnostic instrument. It can identify people who are likely experiencing significant anxiety symptoms and measure symptom severity, but a clinical diagnosis requires a comprehensive evaluation by a qualified healthcare professional. This includes a detailed clinical interview, review of medical history, and consideration of other possible causes of symptoms.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How is anxiety different from normal worry?</summary>
        <p>Normal worry is a proportional, time-limited response to identifiable stressors that does not significantly impair functioning. Anxiety disorder involves worry that is excessive, persistent (lasting months or longer), difficult to control, often disproportionate to actual threats, and accompanied by physical symptoms like muscle tension and sleep disturbance. The critical distinction is whether the worry significantly interferes with your ability to function in daily life.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What are the most effective treatments for anxiety?</summary>
        <p>The treatments with the strongest evidence for anxiety disorders include cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT), which is considered the gold standard psychological treatment; SSRI and SNRI medications, which help regulate brain chemistry; and lifestyle modifications including regular exercise, adequate sleep, stress management, and reducing caffeine and alcohol. Many people benefit most from a combination of these approaches, tailored to their specific type and severity of anxiety.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

